Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

1.Which genres are most popular from year to year?

2.What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

In [35]:
# plotting scatter plot for revenue to value count for clearer analysis
def vote_to_revenue(df):
    df.plot(y='vote_count', x= 'revenue_adj', kind = 'scatter',color = 'green')
    y= df.vote_count
    x = df.revenue_adj
    m, b = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
    plt.plot(x, m*x+b, color = 'orange')
vote_to_revenue(df)
In [36]:
# Removing zero values from budget then plotting scatter plot for revenue to budget for clearer analysis
def budget_to_revenue(df):
    df[df.budget_adj != 0].plot(y='budget_adj', x= 'revenue_adj', kind = 'scatter', color = 'green')
    y = df.budget_adj
    x = df.revenue_adj
    m, b = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
    plt.plot(x, m*x+b, color = 'orange');
budget_to_revenue(df)
In [37]:
# making new dataframe with the top 25% of movies revenue then counting movie genres for them
def top_genres_count(df):
    df_g = df.query('revenue_adj >= 1.526580e+08')
    df_g['genres'].value_counts().plot(kind = 'bar', color = 'green',figsize = (10,5));
top_genres_count(df)
In [38]:
# checking out if there is an outlier directors so they have effect on our revenue factor analysis
def top_directors(df):
    df_g = df.query('revenue_adj >= 1.526580e+08')
    return df_g['director'].value_counts()

Conclusions:¶

From the previos visualization we see that over 56 years the top 3 popular genres were (Adventure, Animation, Fantasy), then the rest of genres came with minimal difference.¶

In the next section we will see if the genres with high popularity will also have high revenues or not.¶

Q2: What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?¶

Limitations:¶

Limitation in answering this question was in zero values of Revenue (53% of revenue data were zero values), and that was big precentage to take either mean or median to fill them as they will have a big misleading impact on our analysis, so we have removed them.¶

Also 49.5% of budget values are zero values that have been removed too but only at plotting the correlation so they will not affect our revenue analysis except in the direct relation between them.¶

Conclutions:¶

From the previous graphs we can see that:¶

1. there is positive correlation between (budget, vote count) and revenue, there is also some outliers in these scatter plots but not too much.¶

2. we see that (Movie genres with top 25% revenues) bar chart that top 4 revnue movie genres over the 64 years are (Action, Comedy, Drame then Adventure), and this answers our last question in the previous section that the top popular genres always have high revenues, there is no relation between revenue and popularity.¶

3. we also see in (Top 20 Directors repeated for the top 25% movie revenues) pie chart that directors have impact on revenues, and i only included it after analysis because there is outliers in it, when we find that 10% of the 25% of hishest revenue movies over 64 years are directed by one director, That needs a great spot on it.¶
